and photography during the Rif War and what did this portrayal reveal about conflicting visions of Spanish identity?Runner-up for the 2017-18 AHGBI-Spanish Embassy Publication Prize This book examines how anxieties about colonial power and national identity are reflected in Spanish literature, journalism, and photography of Moroccan Muslim and Jewish cultures during the Spanish colonisation of Northern Morocco from 1909 to 1927. This understudied period, known as the Rif War, is highly significant because of its role in shaping the identities that came into conflict in the Spanish Civil War (1936-39). Furthermore, the book makes a key contribution to Spanish colonial studies by offering a comparative analysis of Spanish representations of the Iberian Peninsula's cultural and historical relationship with Moroccan Muslims and Jews in this context, showing how conflicting visions of Spanish identity are portrayed through and in relation to them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJews in literature. 0aMuslims in literature. 0aNational characteristics, Spanish, in literature. 0aRif Revolt, 1909xLiterature and the revolt. 0aRif Revolt, 1909xPhotography. 0aRif Revolt, 1921-1926xLiterature and the revolt. 0aRif Revolt, 1921-1926xPhotography. 0aSpanish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aHispanic Studies. 4aIslamic Studies. 4aJewish Studies. 4aModern History. 4aModern Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aMoroccan culture.  aRif War.  aSpanish colonialism.  aSpanish identity.  aSpanish literature.  aSpanish-Moroccan relations.  acolonial power.  acultural conflict.  acultural identity.  acultural influences.  acultural portrayals.  acultural representation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewe